# Bandpass Filter Tuning PRD

## 1. Purpose
This document defines a focused diagnostic and tuning plan for the Phase 2
Ormsby bandpass comb filters, with emphasis on:
- Passband width vs. expected design
- Envelope smoothness and wobble sources
- Frequency-vs-time trace stability

This is a supplementary PRD. It does not change Phase 1/3 deliverables.

## 2. Scope
In scope
- Phase 2 comb filters (AI-2 to AI-4)
- Filter kernel design and response diagnostics
- Envelope behavior characterization
- Parametric cross-checks (MPM/Prony/ESPRIT) as validation only

Out of scope
- New trading logic
- Rewriting Phase 1/3 pipelines
- Major refactors of core library modules

## 3. Current Observations
- Comb filter kernels are long (NW=1999), which tends to narrow peaks.
- Modulate-method analytic BP construction may round shoulders vs. idealized
  trapezoids, affecting apparent width.
- Envelope wobble is expected if multiple close lines exist within a passband.

## 4. Hypotheses
H1: Narrow peaks are caused by long kernels (NW) and/or modulate construction,
    not by a lack of weights.
H2: Envelope wobble is primarily multi-line beating within each passband, not
    filter instability.
H3: Frequency-vs-time jitter is amplified by raw peak detection and can be
    reduced with light gating or smoothing without altering true lines.

## 5. Diagnostics (No Code Changes Required)
D1. Single-tone sanity test
- Filter a single sinusoid at each filter center frequency.
- Expect near-constant envelope; any wobble indicates filter design issues.

D2. Two-tone beat test
- Filter two sinusoids spaced by ~0.2 to 0.4 rad/yr.
- Envelope beat period should match expected 2*pi / delta_omega.

D3. Measure actual bandwidth
- Compute -3 dB or -6 dB widths from FFT response and compare with
  w2-w3 and w1-w4 targets.

D4. Sum response ripple
- Verify composite gain across the comb bank is near unity
  in the target band (7.6 to 12.0 rad/yr).

## 6. Tuning Experiments (Minimal Changes)
E1. Vary NW
- Test NW in {799, 1199, 1599, 1999, 2599}.
- Measure bandwidth, ripple, and envelope smoothness.

E2. Adjust skirt/passband widths
- Test passband_width in {0.2, 0.3} and skirt_width in {0.3, 0.4}.
- Compare peak broadening vs. leakage.

E3. Compare BP construction methods
- Compare modulate vs subtract for analytic BP.
- Expect more exact trapezoid shape with subtract; expect smoother
  phase with modulate.

E4. Envelope smoothing (display only)
- Apply light median or Savitzky-Golay smoothing to envelope for plots
  without altering measurements.

## 7. Parametric Cross-Checks
P1. Matrix Pencil Method (MPM)
- Use short sliding windows (e.g., 104 to 156 weeks).
- Estimate dominant lines and compare to comb bank medians.

P2. Prony / Kumaresan-Tufts
- Apply to same windows and compare line stability.

P3. ESPRIT or MUSIC
- Use as a sensitivity check for closely spaced lines.

## 8. Acceptance Criteria
- Measured passband width within +/-10% of target (w3-w2).
- Composite gain ripple within +/-1.5 dB across 7.6 to 12.0 rad/yr.
- Single-tone envelope variance below 5% of mean amplitude.
- Two-tone envelope wobble matches expected beat period within 10%.
- Parametric line estimates agree with comb medians within 0.1 to 0.2 rad/yr.

## 9. Deliverables
- Short diagnostic report (1-2 pages) with:
  - Bandwidth and ripple tables
  - Example envelope plots (single-tone and two-tone)
  - Summary of optimal NW and width settings
- Optional appendix: parametric method comparisons

## 10. Notes
- All experiments use DJIA weekly data (1921-04-29 to 1965-05-21) unless
  a synthetic test is specified.
- Do not change Phase 1/3 reproduction outputs as part of this work.
